        <descriptionSet>
            <description href="http://www.metmuseum.org/collection/the-collection-online/search/45434" pref="false" source="Metropolitan Museum of Art" dataDate="2016-06-02-11-05-59">
                <text>The breathtaking composition of this woodblock print, said to have inspired Debussy’s La Mer (The Sea) and Rilke’s Der Berg (The Mountain), ensures its reputation as an icon of world art. Hokusai cleverly played with perspective to make Japan’s grandest mountain appear as a small triangular mound within the hollow of the cresting wave. The artist became famous for his landscapes created using a palette of indigo and imported Prussian blue.</text>
                <author>
                    <name refid="126238294" type="corporate" vocab="viaf">Metropolitan Museum of Art</name>
                    <role type="code" vocab="marcrelator">aut</role>
                </author>
            </description>
            <description pref="true" dataDate="2015-11-11-16-26-42">
                <text>The large wave dominates the scene, with the small mountain in the background. It is said to have inspired both Debussy’s “La Mer” and Rilke’s “Der Berg.”</text>
                <author>
                    <name refid="131347215" type="corporate" vocab="viaf">Visual Resources Association</name>
                    <role type="code" vocab="marcrelator">aut</role>
                </author>
            </description>
        </descriptionSet>
